      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>GBP Photos</strong> are images uploaded to a Google Business Profile that showcase the business, team, products, and services. Both owner uploads and customer contributions appear in Google Search and Maps results. Businesses with photos see <strong>42% more direction requests and 35% more website clicks</strong> than those without, and photos influence <strong>90%+ of local searchers</strong> using Google Maps.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Direction request lift</div>
            <div class="tms-value"><span class="http-code-chip ok">+42%</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO · GBP</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Min resolution</div>
            <div class="tms-value">720 x 720 px</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Photos are the fastest lever in local SEO. A well-shot cover photo and a full library of interior, exterior, team, and product images can lift engagement inside a single month — with zero content or link work.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What are GBP Photos?</h2>
        <p>GBP Photos are the images that appear inside a Google Business Profile. Two sources contribute: photos the business owner uploads through the GBP dashboard, and photos customers upload alongside reviews or check-ins. Both flow into the same photo library and Google's algorithm selects which images to feature — including the cover photo — based on quality, category, and engagement signals.</p>
        <p>Photos are organized into required and optional categories. The required set includes logo, cover, interior, exterior, and team. Optional categories depend on the business type — food and drink for restaurants, product photos for retail, at-work photos for service businesses.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's photo weight in local rankings</div>
          <p>Google's own business insights data shows photo-rich profiles receive <strong>520% more calls</strong> and <strong>2,717% more direction requests</strong> than photo-poor profiles. Photos also influence <strong>90%+ of local searchers</strong> using Google Maps, according to industry surveys.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why GBP Photos matter</h2>
        <p>Photos serve as the visual first impression before a customer visits, and they carry ranking weight through the engagement they drive. Four reasons every local business obsesses over photos:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>First-impression trust.</strong> A cover photo showing a real storefront or team beats a generic map pin every time. Trust builds faster with imagery than with copy.</li>
          <li><strong>Engagement lift.</strong> Businesses with photos see 42% more direction requests and 35% more website clicks. Photo-rich profiles (100+) see up to 520% more calls.</li>
          <li><strong>Cover photo control.</strong> Google picks the cover from your library. Upload strategic images and you influence which face of the business searchers see first.</li>
          <li><strong>Freshness signal.</strong> Monthly photo uploads contribute to Google's freshness signal, which correlates with higher Local Pack rankings.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How GBP Photos work</h2>
        <p>Owner uploads and customer contributions merge into a single photo library. Google's algorithm picks feature photos — cover, first-in-search, gallery order — based on resolution, relevance to category, and engagement.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Photo requirements</span><br>
          Resolution <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">720 x 720 px minimum</span><br>
          Format <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">JPG or PNG</span><br>
          Content <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">real business photos, no stock, no watermarks</span><br>
          Categories <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">logo, cover, interior, exterior, team, product</span><br>
          Cadence <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">monthly refresh minimum</span>
        </div>

        <h3>Owner-uploaded photos</h3>
        <p>Added through the GBP dashboard, one at a time or bulk. Owner photos generally take precedence in the gallery ordering because Google can verify the source.</p>

        <h3>Customer-uploaded photos</h3>
        <p>Added alongside reviews or check-ins. Add authenticity and user-generated content value, but the business owner cannot delete them directly — only flag for Google's review under guideline violations.</p>

        <h2 id="types">GBP Photo categories</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Category</th><th>Required?</th><th>Best count</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Cover</strong></td><td>Yes</td><td>1</td><td>Hero image shown first in Search and Maps</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Logo</strong></td><td>Yes</td><td>1</td><td>Brand icon on the profile</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Interior</strong></td><td>Yes</td><td>5-10</td><td>Space customers will experience</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Exterior</strong></td><td>Yes</td><td>3-5</td><td>Storefront for wayfinding</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Team</strong></td><td>Recommended</td><td>3-5</td><td>People behind the business — trust builder</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Product / Food / At-work</strong></td><td>Category-dependent</td><td>10+</td><td>What you actually sell or do</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real GBP Photo examples</h2>
        <p>Two case studies from businesses that treated photos as their primary local lever.</p>

        <h3>1. Dental office — 25 photos in month one</h3>
        <p>Uploaded 25 photos across every required category — waiting room, treatment rooms, exterior, team headshots, and equipment. Listing engagement (calls + direction requests + website clicks) jumped 60% in the first month post-upload with no other changes to the profile.</p>

        <h3>2. Landscaping company — project portfolio</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Photo strategy</span><br>
          Uploaded <span class="uf-new">40 project photos</span> organized by type<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Front yard makeovers<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Backyard patios<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Xeriscaping / drought-tolerant<br>
          <span class="uf-status">30% of new leads attributed to photo visibility</span>
        </div>

        <h3>3. Boutique retail — monthly seasonal refresh</h3>
        <p>Added 8-10 new product and window-display photos on the first of every month. Held Local Pack top 3 through category-crowded holiday shopping seasons because Google read the profile as consistently active.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">GBP Photos vs GBP Products — where each fits</h2>
        <p>Photos and Products both use images, but they serve different purposes on the profile. Photos build trust and engagement broadly. Products power a structured catalog with prices and CTAs.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use GBP Photos when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Showcasing the space, team, or brand</li>
              <li>Building general trust and engagement</li>
              <li>Filling required category slots</li>
              <li>Signaling freshness with monthly uploads</li>
              <li>Any business type — universal</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use GBP Products when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Presenting a structured catalog with prices</li>
              <li>Capturing product-specific search queries</li>
              <li>Driving purchase intent with CTAs</li>
              <li>Retail, restaurant, or productized services</li>
              <li>Complementing — not replacing — general photos</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for GBP Photos in 2026</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Upload at least 25 photos as a baseline.</strong> Fill every required category before adding more to any one bucket.</li>
          <li><strong>Refresh monthly.</strong> Even 3-5 fresh photos per month keeps the freshness signal alive.</li>
          <li><strong>Use real business photos, never stock.</strong> Google's image quality signals penalize obvious stock imagery.</li>
          <li><strong>Shoot at 1080p or higher.</strong> Minimum is 720x720, but higher resolution photos display better across devices.</li>
          <li><strong>Include team photos.</strong> Faces build trust faster than product shots for service businesses.</li>
          <li><strong>Add captions and geotags where possible.</strong> Metadata helps Google understand image context.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor customer photos weekly.</strong> Flag anything violating guidelines. Encourage happy customers to upload after positive experiences.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — one great cover photo, nothing else</div>
          <p>A stunning cover with only 3 other photos in the gallery underperforms a mediocre cover with 40 photos across every category. Volume plus category coverage beats hero imagery alone.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common GBP Photo mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Stock imagery.</strong> Detectable and flaggable. Real photos always outperform.</li>
          <li><strong>Watermarks and heavy filters.</strong> Both violate photo guidelines and can result in removal.</li>
          <li><strong>Uploading once and stopping.</strong> Freshness decays. Monthly cadence beats a big batch followed by silence.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring customer photos.</strong> Never flagging inappropriate uploads lets bad content sit on the profile.</li>
          <li><strong>Missing required categories.</strong> A profile with no exterior shot loses trust for foot-traffic businesses.</li>
          <li><strong>Low resolution.</strong> Anything under 720x720 gets rejected or downranked in the gallery.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="how-thestacc-helps">How theStacc helps</h2>
        <p>theStacc's Local SEO module tracks photo counts, category coverage, and upload cadence across your Google Business Profile — and flags gaps against category leaders in your market. Monthly refresh reminders and a photo brief generator make the ongoing work repeatable without adding to your team's workload.</p>

